INSERT INTO `text_lesson_translations` (`id`, `text_lesson_id`, `locale`, `title`, `summary`, `content`) VALUES
(1, 13, 'en', 'Hello, World!', 'Get started learning Python with DataCamp\'s free Intro to Python tutorial. Learn Data Science by completing interactive coding challenges and watching videos by expert instructors. Start Now!', '<div>Python is a very simple language, and has a very straightforward syntax. It encourages programmers to program without boilerplate (prepared) code. The simplest directive in Python is the \"print\" directive - it simply prints out a line (and also includes a newline, unlike in C).</div><div><br></div><div>There are two major Python versions, Python 2 and Python 3. Python 2 and 3 are quite different. This tutorial uses Python 3, because it more semantically correct and supports newer features.</div><div><br></div><div>For example, one difference between Python 2 and 3 is the print statement. In Python 2, the \"print\" statement is not a function, and therefore it is invoked without parentheses. However, in Python 3, it is a function, and must be invoked with parentheses.</div>'),
(2, 14, 'en', 'Learning', 'Before getting started, you may want to find out which IDEs and text editors are tailored to make Python editing easy, browse the list of introductory books, or look at code samples that you might find helpful.', '<div>There is a list of tutorials suitable for experienced programmers on the BeginnersGuide/Tutorials page. There is also a list of resources in other languages which might be useful if English is not your first language.</div><div><br></div><div>The online documentation is your first port of call for definitive information. There is a fairly brief tutorial that gives you basic information about the language and gets you started. You can follow this by looking at the library reference for a full description of Python\'s many libraries and the language reference for a complete (though somewhat dry) explanation of Python\'s syntax. If you are looking for common Python recipes and patterns, you can browse the ActiveState Python Cookbook</div>'),
(3, 15, 'en', 'Looking for Something Specific?', 'If you want to know whether a particular application, or a library with particular functionality, is available in Python there are a number of possible sources of information.', '<p>If you want to know whether a particular application, or a library with particular functionality, is available in Python there are a number of possible sources of information. The Python web site provides a Python Package Index (also known as the Cheese Shop, a reference to the Monty Python script of that name). There is also a search page for a number of sources of Python-related information. Failing that, just Google for a phrase including the word \'\'python\'\' and you may well get the result you need. If all else fails, ask on the python newsgroup and there\'s a good chance someone will put you on the right track.</p><p>Python is an interpreted high-level general-purpose programming language. Python\'s design philosophy emphasizes code readability with its notable use of significant indentation. Its language constructs as well as its object-oriented approach aim to help programmers write clear, logical code for small and large-scale projects.[30]</p><p><br></p><p>Python is dynamically-typed and garbage-collected. It supports multiple programming paradigms, including structured (particularly, procedural), object-oriented and functional programming. Python is often described as a \"batteries included\" language due to its comprehensive standard library.[31]</p><p><br></p><p>Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s, as a successor to the ABC programming language, and first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.[32] Python 2.0 was released in 2000 and introduced new features, such as list comprehensions and a garbage collection system using reference counting. Python 3.0 was released in 2008 and was a major revision of the language that is not completely backward-compatible and much Python 2 code does not run unmodified on Python 3. Python 2 was discontinued with version 2.7.18 in 2020.[33]</p><p><br></p><p>Python consistently ranks as one of the most popular programming languages.</p>'),
(13, 21, 'en', 'Introduction to Business Analysis', ' Requirements have always been a concern in project management the focus and importance of requirements work have continued to gain more attention in the industry as organization\'s began to recognize how to use business analysis to the competitive advantage, there is an increasing demand for practitioners with the required business analysis skills.', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/XsKdzHVEXig\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe><br></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\"><br></span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">INTRODUCTION</span></p><p></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">&nbsp;</span>Requirements have always been a concern in project management the focus and importance of requirements work have continued to gain more attention in the industry as organization\'s began to recognize how to use business analysis to the competitive advantage, there is an increasing demand for practitioners with the required business analysis skills. In this video, we are going to learn about the fundamental concepts of business analysis we will begin with understanding what is business analysis what you do in business analysis and how you do business analysis this will be followed by an understanding of the business analyst role and the skills needed to effectively perform business analysis on programs and projects. We will close out with an understanding of the key terms related to business analysis that will be used frequently in the upcoming videos then we will learn about the requirements classifications of key&nbsp;stakeholders and finally,&nbsp;the distinction&nbsp;between requirements and design let\'s&nbsp;start with understanding what is&nbsp;business analysis. Business analysis enables a change in&nbsp;the enterprise by defining needs and&nbsp;recommending solutions that deliver&nbsp;value to the stakeholder. Let\'s dig deeper and understand what you&nbsp;do in&nbsp;business analysis.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">INTRODUCTION TO ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES</span></p><p>Business analysis is the application of knowledge skills tools and techniques to determine problems and identify business needs identify and recommend viable solutions for meeting those needs elicit documents and manage requirements to meet business and project objectives and facilitate the successful implementation of the product service or result of the program or project. Let\'s delve into a little more detail and understand how you perform business analyses the tasks or business analysis refine the broad definition of specific&nbsp;information by facilitating the&nbsp;identification of problems,&nbsp;opportunity understanding the business environmental&nbsp;context and constraints analyzing&nbsp;requirements verifying requirements and&nbsp;evaluating solutions.&nbsp;</p><p>Finally,&nbsp;business analysis involves effort and&nbsp;a variety of domains from identifying&nbsp;business needs to solution&nbsp;implementation let\'s move on to&nbsp;understanding the business analyst role&nbsp;and the skills needed to effectively&nbsp;perform business analysis on programs&nbsp;and projects.</p><p>Who does business analysis? Let’s&nbsp;find out next a business analyst&nbsp;is a person who performs business&nbsp;analysis tasks in the context of&nbsp;programs and projects. There&nbsp;are common job titles&nbsp;for people who perform business analysis&nbsp;including&nbsp;business architect, business&nbsp;systems analyst, data analyst, enterprise analyst management&nbsp;consultant,&nbsp;process analyst,&nbsp;product&nbsp;manager, requirements engineer and</p><p></p><p>systems analyst.</p><p>BUSINESS ANALYST SKILL SET</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">With a firm understanding of the business, analysis domain let\'s understand the skill set and expertise needed for the business analyst role anyone performing business analysis activities on programs and products should have analytical skills business and industry knowledge communication skills including strong business writing and verbal communication skills, conflict management, skills in creative and critical thinking cultural awareness, decision-making, facilitation, issue management skills leadership skills, learning skills, negotiation skills, organizational skills, problem-solving ability.</p><p>To work in a team environment including virtual teams’ technical awareness systems thinking presentation skills political awareness familiarity with multiple projects and development methodologies to have a complete understanding of these skills please see the skill assessment tool online. Now that we understand the skill set required to be a successful business analyst let\'s see what business analysts do.</p><p></p><p>Business analysts play a role in aligning the design and delivered solutions with the needs of stakeholders the activities that business analysts perform include understanding enterprise problems and goals analyzing needs and solutions devising strategies driving change and facilitating stakeholder the collaboration&nbsp;completes our understanding of what&nbsp;is entailed in business analysis&nbsp;and who could be a successful business&nbsp;analyst.</p>'),
(14, 22, 'en', 'The scope of the Business Analyst’s job (The roles and responsibilities of a BA)', 'Roles and Responsibilities of a Business Analyst', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/O-U7FdqPBSQ\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe><br></p><p><br></p><p><strong>Roles and Responsibilities of a Business Analyst</strong></p><p><img class=\"zls-tinymce-img\" src=\"/_lms/api/portal/right-click-academy/course/6352450000000011001/lesson/6352450000000015005/file/6352450000000027045\"></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Welcome! Are you aspiring to become a business analyst? If yes, then you should have a clear idea of what a BA does and what their roles, as well as responsibilities,&nbsp;are at their workplace. In today\'s session, we are going to discuss exactly that. So, without further ado, let\'s get started with today\'s agenda.</p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We will begin this session by discussing a little about the history behind the business analyst role. Next, we will answer the question, \"Who is a business analyst?\"&nbsp;After&nbsp;that, we will look at the responsibilities of a BA in detail. Moving on, we will discuss the skills required to be a business analyst. Finally, we will end this session by taking a look at the business analyst job descriptions posted by some popular companies. I hope you are okay with the agenda, so let\'s get started.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img class=\"zls-tinymce-img\" src=\"/_lms/api/portal/right-click-academy/course/6352450000000011001/lesson/6352450000000015005/file/6352450000000027047\" alt=\"\"></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As you&nbsp;might have known, business analysis has evolved extensively over the last two decades, and business analysts have established themselves in every department of every organization. How did we get here? What sparked the birth of business analysis? During the initial days of its evolution in the early \'90s, there was a rapid increase in the need to incorporate the use of IT, and businesses\' data storage was enhanced. User-friendly programs and new object-oriented programs such as Java were invented. The first graphical user interface came into being. All of these led to a boom in information technology. Although the value of technology was apparent, it was still very expensive. But why did organizations want to utilize information technology to get better results? They didn\'t have very good experience planning tasks. The systems were developed considering the latest technology, but without reconsidering the necessity to develop it, their relevant use, and the target audience. Also, despite their expertise in their respective fields, communication between business users and programmers was hard. As a result, customers were unsatisfied, and a large sum of money was being spent on software rewrites, updates, maintenance, and resolving software defects.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p>&nbsp;<img class=\"zls-tinymce-img\" src=\"/_lms/api/portal/right-click-academy/course/6352450000000011001/lesson/6352450000000015005/file/6352450000000027049\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Organizations then began to hire a group of technical experts who would simply translate requirements into lines of code. They were known as system analysts. System analysts had the technical outlook for the products to be developed, but they were lacking in business acumen that would make these systems more productive. There was a great need for someone who would analyze the need for the system, and its requirements, and then provide an accurate definition of the IT requirements required to develop the system. Thus, business analysis was born, and the role of business analysts came into existence. Before we delve more into who a business analyst is, let\'s take a look at what the business analysis practice means in general. Business analysis is the process of enabling change within an organization by doing three things, which are identifying business needs or requirements, understanding and analyzing those requirements, and recommending relevant solutions that deliver value to stakeholders.&nbsp;</p><p><img class=\"zls-tinymce-img\" src=\"/_lms/api/portal/right-click-academy/course/6352450000000011001/lesson/6352450000000015005/file/6352450000000027051\"></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To understand who a business analyst is, let\'s take a look at this example. Let\'s say you want to build a house&nbsp;what is the first thing that you would do? Right after you buy a piece of land or plot, you hire an architect. The architect engages with you, asking a bunch of questions such as what style of house you want to build, your budget, the type of roofing, the number of bedrooms, a stylish kitchen, and other things. post that the architect draws up a business plan and gets it confirmed from you then he or she will contact the builders&nbsp;and discuss the implementation of the plan with them as work progresses the architect would keep monitoring the progress to ensure the house is built according to the plan and your need on a few occasions,&nbsp;unforeseen problems might arise,&nbsp;requiring the plans to be re-examined and some changes to be made,&nbsp;but eventually you get your house built.&nbsp;A&nbsp;business analyst\'s role is more like that of an architect, just that instead of building a house,&nbsp;a business analyst is acting as an agent of change within an organization.&nbsp;Now instead of producing plans as in the case of the architect,&nbsp;a business analyst produces needs,&nbsp;or you can say requirements these requirements are then used by the IT team to build new systems or modify the existing systems in place within the organization while work is in progress.&nbsp;The business analyst should be ready to deal with issues.&nbsp;Answer questions and support the business in implementing the required changes now that you know what a business analyst does,&nbsp;let’s&nbsp;get into his or her mind and learn how a business analyst thinks.&nbsp;A&nbsp;business analyst is a person who has strong logical and analytical skills adequate technical skills strong business acumen,&nbsp;problem-solving skills, strong interpersonal skills, and negotiation skills.&nbsp;They have a detail-oriented mind and are always analyzing everything.&nbsp;Their minds are constantly running through questions about activities they observe what is being done and why did this happen;&nbsp;is there an alternative are the rules being followed can we consider this?</p><p><img class=\"zls-tinymce-img\" src=\"/_lms/api/portal/right-click-academy/course/6352450000000011001/lesson/6352450000000015005/file/6352450000000027055\"></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Are any exceptions being made? Should the rules be changed? Is there a way to turn this problem into an opportunity? Are we being as efficient as possible? What are the causes and effects, and other forms of creative questions? make business analysts a valuable asset in an organization now let us take a look at the business analyst\'s responsibilities and duties based on the different phases of a project the first thing you need to know is that the business analyst role is a multifaceted role by that I mean the responsibilities of a BA changes from organization to organization yet on any given day the activities that business analysts perform include the following; identifying the multifaceted organizational problems and opportunities for improvement in business operations and processes. Understanding the intricacies of a project is very crucial for BAs eliciting relevant documents and requirements and using those requirements to get the IT team on&nbsp;board and understand what the client wants; that\'s one of the biggest responsibilities.</p><p><img class=\"zls-tinymce-img\" src=\"/_lms/api/portal/right-click-academy/course/6352450000000011001/lesson/6352450000000015005/file/6352450000000027057\"></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Also, it is extremely critical for any BA to effectively document the findings so that each client requirement is efficiently mentioned and nothing is left to chance. The most important responsibility of a business analyst is to analyze the information collected in a detailed manner. The analysis phase is the stage during which a BA reviews the elements in detail, asserting clearly what the business needs to do to achieve its goal. During this stage, the BA will also be required to interact with the development team and then the technical&nbsp;architects,&nbsp;which brings us to the next responsibility of communicating with a broad range of people, the next responsibility of a BA are to interact with the business stakeholders and subject matter experts to understand their problems and needs. As a business analyst, it is important to create and deliver quality presentations. A good business analyst also needs to dedicate countless hours actively communicating back and forth more than just speaking he or she needs to listen and recognize verbal and nonverbal information the next responsibility is to devise strategies to design new systems or modify existing business systems or&nbsp;processes the most important job of the business analyst is to spend time identifying multiple options for solving challenges and then help pick the best one</p><p><img class=\"zls-tinymce-img\" src=\"/_lms/api/portal/right-click-academy/course/6352450000000011001/lesson/6352450000000015005/file/6352450000000027059\"></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A business analyst makes specific IT recommendations and supports the IT team in the implementation phase in any way he or she can if you think the responsibilities of the BAS end in the implementation phase you are wrong. Ensuring that the product is functioning well as it is designed and that it satisfies the user requirements is one of the most vital responsibilities of the business analyst. User acceptance testing is the only possible and accepted way to ensure this apart from this a business analyst sometimes creates system documentation and user manuals he or she develops informative coherent and usable documents for professional success so guys these are some basic responsibilities of a business analyst the role of a business analyst is constantly evolving and changing, especially as companies rely more on data to advise business operations. The work that business analysts do is incredibly diverse. Moving on, let us answer the question of what it takes to become a business analyst.</p><p><img class=\"zls-tinymce-img\" src=\"/_lms/api/portal/right-click-academy/course/6352450000000011001/lesson/6352450000000015005/file/6352450000000027061\"></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Business analysis requires both technical and core business skills. According to the international institute of business analysis, some of the most important skills for a business analyst are effective communication skills including technical writing skills analytical thinking, problem-solving creative thinking, relevant industry knowledge technical skills including data visualization statistical analysis, software business intelligence elicitation skills, and understanding of networks databases and other technology. To make all the concepts that we discussed more clear let us take a look at business analysis job descriptions posted by companies in the job search portals as I mentioned earlier the work BAs do is incredibly diverse which has led to many changes in job titles roles and management levels.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n\r\n</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When looking for BA jobs keep in mind that a business analyst is not always referred to as a business analyst, alternative titles for this job role include but are not limited to IT project coordinator, functional analyst, information process analyst, agile analyst, and many others.&nbsp; Your core responsibilities will include a combination of things like analysis communication, technical expertise innovations, identifying issues, and others. As for the qualifications you need to have either a bachelor\'s degree or master\'s degree in relevant domains in addition to that you need to have excellent communication time management and collaboration skills, amongst other things.</p>'),
(15, 23, 'en', 'Business analysis tools and techniques', 'Often, business analysis is described as translating business needs into solution requirements. This sounds so simple, but in truth, there are many steps and techniques that are used to get to the final solution requirements to keep things simple.', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/ezSQhea3O0w\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p>Often, business analysis is described as translating business needs into solution requirements. This sounds so simple, but in truth, there are many steps and techniques that are used to get to the final solution requirements to keep things simple. I\'m going to categorize the work into three main categories: understanding the business goals, understanding the current state, and defining the required changes. There are other peripheral activities of a business analyst, but those are often dependent on seniority if you are a contractor or if you\'re specifically doing waterfall, so I\'ll skip those.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The techniques mentioned are generally accepted as being useful for accomplishing the tasks; however, it is always up to you to determine the best way to accomplish each major step, so let\'s get started. Understanding the business goals is critical to being a good business analyst because part of your job is to keep your team, both business and IT, on track to success. At this point, you are simply trying to define why everyone is doing what they are doing depending on your work environment this could be at a program level project level product level or feature level for your part, the techniques you will likely use will be workshops and interviews to gather the information next is understanding the current state of things, and the techniques or tools you choose to use are very dependent on the types of changes that will be made here. You might start with mind maps or context models that will lay out your landscape and help you get an idea of the different parts of the organization that are involved with or impacted by the area that needs to change.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The tools here can vary; all-purpose modelling tools like Visio, Lucid Chart, or Draw IO might be used. PowerPoint can also be used if the model won\'t get too heavy or from there you might have interviews, workshops document analysis and other activities that essentially allow you to collect the information you need the collection of that information will result in the documentation of that information the goal of all this documentation is to ensure that all parties involved understand how things work currently and will eventually serve to point out the areas that need to change this is where you\'ll see the big heavy hitters for business analysts like process models decision models business rules data models data flow diagrams and so forth here once again you can use two all-purpose modeling tools like Visio lucid charts or draw IO and many more for almost all the models you can also use specific business process modeling tools like there\'s Aussie for example the true value of all that work comes when you get to the next step which is defining what needs to be changed here once again you\'ll need to work with the stakeholders have workshops interviews focus groups and other collaborative activities to understand what should change and who gets impacted when you make the change.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Changes might need to be made to the business process and then all the applications that support the business process will subsequently need to make some changes. You might also need to make changes to the data or how the data is collected or moved and all the applications that interact with that data or the business process that you use that data for might need to make adjustments. as well as the correctness of all the models you created will impact how effectively the changes you decide to make will be. Conversely, it will determine how many problems you introduce into the applications or process by ineffectively understanding how they worked and what would break when you changed things. This right here is why a business analyst is so important If you compare this to my vacation planning comparison that I use in my requirements elicitation video, it would be like missing that someone is allergic to something when making dinner reservations or that someone can\'t leave until a certain date when buying plane tickets. Here you are analyzing the models you created and creating future states of those models, which will help you see the areas where changes will need to be made.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to modelling other techniques might be impact analysis, root cause analysis, and business process simulation. If you used a fancy BPM end tool like Brazeau g functional decomposition is a very common way to begin documenting what needs to change. For example, if a high-level business requirement feature or whatever is starting to accept payments online, that functionality might break down into being able to input the credit card information, being able to validate credit card information, being able to store new and being able to store new payment-related data in the database you can already see that this will result in new UI components new data interfaces to perhaps third-party credit card validators and changes to the database structure luckily and likely much more depending on the complexity of your fulfilment systems these changes will be documented as business requirements, functional requirements, use cases user stories wireframes prototypes, acceptance criteria and more here again, you might keep it simple with the tools like Word, PowerPoint or Excel you might have dedicated lifecycle management tools like JIRA agile Trello or version one if you\'re agile, likely this will be dictated by the organization mostly for long-term quality control purposes it\'s important to remember that you don\'t originate any of the data that goes into your documentation; you gather it from stakeholders who are responsible for the success of their domains, and you also aren\'t the final consumer of any of that documentation. Others need it to understand impacts, make decisions, and eventually develop the functionality.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This is why interaction skills, communication skills, and analytical thinking</p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p>skills are so critically important to successful business analysis. I know I went through that pretty quickly and I didn\'t dig too deep into the individual techniques or tools.</p>'),
(16, 24, 'en', 'Jira to document user stories and manage agile projects', 'Jira is an advanced project management tool designed for agile teams to essentially optimize project planning, execution, and tracking.', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/GWxMTvRGIpc\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe><br></p><p><br></p><p>Jira is an advanced project management tool designed for agile teams to essentially optimize project planning, execution, and tracking. The great thing about Jira is they offer a free plan for up to 10 users, which is ideal for agile and innovative</p><p>\r\n</p><p>small teams. Hey team, welcome back to another video. I hope everyone is having a great day now today we\'re going to launch the project management tool called Jira and cover how you can get started with the impressive free plan to manage your dynamic project workflows. Now if you\'re completely new to project management, I recommend looking into Trello as an entry-level project management tool to get started with before you jump into a more advanced software like Jira both of these tools offer exceptional free plans and stem from the same company called Atlassian. Okay, now just quickly before we go ahead and jump right into Jira, consider subscribing if you haven\'t done so already, and that way you\'ll stay updated with actionable videos and tutorials designed to equip you with the skills, knowledge, and tools to grow your small business online. With that quick note out of the way let\'s go ahead and jump straight into this jira tutorial. Okay team, so first things first, what we need to do is sign up for a free jira account. To do this, just head over to atlassian.com software slash jira, and that\'s going to take you to this page. What we want to do is get started for free, and before we get started, it\'s important to note that jira is first and foremost a software development tool for software teams, but you can also create project management workflows that work for different types of businesses, not just software development. In this beginner\'s tutorial, we\'re going to show you an agile process as well as a traditional business workflow. We\'ve already created a fresh new account, and what we\'re going to do is meet you on your dashboard once you\'ve signed up, so go ahead and sign up for free, and we\'ll meet you at your JIRA dashboard. Okay, so we\'ve gone ahead and created a fresh account and logged in to Jira. Remember that Jira as a project management software is first and foremost designed for software development, and the first thing we\'re going to show you today is how to use Jira to create a project management workflow for a software project. So the whole idea of software development stems from creating an agile process. An agile process is divided into five stages: functionality, planning, implementation, testing, and the review stage. Once you reach the review stage, you can either build your software or return to the planning stage, depending on whether you discover any issues along the way.</p>'),
(17, 25, 'en', 'Excel for analysis, reporting and data visualization', 'Hello everyone my name is Dany Hoter and I’m a Senior Program Manager in the Excel team at Microsoft.', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/B22arpiRTes\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe><br></p><p><br></p><p>Hello everyone my name is Dany Hoter and I’m a Senior Program Manager in the Excel team at Microsoft. And this course is going to be about analyzing and visualizing data in Excel. Actually, I’m gonna use Excel 2016. Originally it was supposed to be with Excel 2016, but we decided to just call it Excel. Because you’ll be able to follow this not only with Excel 2016 but</p><p>also with Excel 2013 and with a little bit more difficulty also with Excel 2010. Now, I’m gonna be covering areas of importing data into Excel, creating models of data in Excel and using new tools that were added to Excel in the last versions. Let’s go straight into our first module. And in this module, actually I’m going to show you things which are not necessarily new. I’m gonna show you data analysis using data in Excel, in the grid of Excel. And most of you will be, hopefully, familiar to you but<br>I’m going to cover it and then show the differences between this classic way of analyzing data and the new tools that I’m going to show you for the modules. So let me open my first file here in Excel and let’s understand how people are doing data analysis and excel for years.</p>'),
