(72, 80, 'en', 'Ideation Techniques', 'Ideation Techniques', '<h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Crazy-8s and Sketching</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/9VS8bQWlQAg\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p><br></p><ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Tools to Run a Crazy-8 Sketch Session</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">When\r\n you\'re running an ideation session using the Crazy-8 Technique, you \r\nwill want to have a way to keep time. Remember, you\'re only supposed to \r\nwork on each frame of your folded paper for only 1 minute. When I use \r\nthis technique, I use an online Crazy-8 Interval Timer available&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"http://www.intervaltimer.com/timers/7005809-crazy-8\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. This tool is free and web-based (and is the first result when searching for&nbsp;<code class=\"chakra-code css-p3l7io\">Crazy-8 Timer</code>&nbsp;on Google), which means I can quickly pull it up when inspiration strikes.<span></span></p> </div>   </div>   </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Bad Idea Sketches</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/Ym4wUFS9rp0\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p><br></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Introducing the Idea of Bad Ideas</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">When you\'re working with stakeholders, you\'ll need to explain why you\'re using certain techniques. It\'s a&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">good idea</em>&nbsp;to introduce the&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Bad Idea</em>&nbsp;technique\r\n clearly before jumping in. You should communicate clearly that this \r\ntechnique is a warmup to make sure everyone in the room is ready to \r\ndesign. When using any of these tools in a workshop, it is a good idea \r\nto set expectations for how long things will take—people will be more \r\nopen to trying something different if they know it will only take 5 \r\nminutes.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">&nbsp;</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">&nbsp;</p> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Combinatorics</h2> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"vds-loading vds-loading--md\"> <div class=\"vds-loading__children\"> <div class=\"_1UN_ejel6QzQCa_M5Nn4bu\"> <div class=\"_2lGVVA99VY-snhn6dzPP-z\"> <div class=\"_3h3jXAJ1HmC2_sa49itKME _2nvHtsDYiD14gMJ8MpUp2c\">&nbsp;<iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/k8fiDwb9eQg\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></div><div class=\"_3h3jXAJ1HmC2_sa49itKME _2nvHtsDYiD14gMJ8MpUp2c\"><br></div><div class=\"_3h3jXAJ1HmC2_sa49itKME _2nvHtsDYiD14gMJ8MpUp2c\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">When to Use These Techniques</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">These\r\n are a few techniques you can use while ideating alone or with your team\r\n in a workshop. Ultimately, you won\'t always use each technique and you \r\nmight find yourself organically trying something different.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">These\r\n techniques are especially useful early in the design process before \r\nyou\'re settled on a clear direction. But you might find yourself \r\nrevisiting techniques for more specific parts of your design problem. \r\nFor example, you might use the&nbsp;<code class=\"chakra-code css-p3l7io\">Crazy-8</code>&nbsp;technique to quickly sketch out 8 different ways a form layout might work on a page.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">I\r\n like to use these techniques when I feel that my team and I are blocked\r\n and the direction is totally unclear. Usually, the 10 minutes spent \r\nideating is less than the hours we would have spent thinking about what \r\nto do next.<span></span></p> </div>   </div>   </div>          <div class=\"zw-flex zw-fl-normal zw-fl-grow zls-overflow-hidden\"><div class=\"zls-right-col zw-flex zw-flex-column zw-fl-normal zw-fl-grow zls-overflow-hidden\" id=\"lesson-container\">         </div> </div>   <div id=\"manualGotoTop\" class=\"zw-pos-fx zls-goto-top zw-animate zw-hide zw-show\"> </div><div id=\"popup-container\" class=\"zw-main-container\">    </div>\r\n<div id=\"zw-searchResultsWrap\"></div> \r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div id=\"lyte-components-div\"><template class=\"zw-block {{if(isBlankSlate,\'zls-stop-animation\')}} {{tableClass}}\">    </template>\r\n\r\n\r\n<template class=\"zls-iframe-wrapper zls-document-element {{if(showNativeFullscreen,\'zw-pos-re\')}}\">  </template></div></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>   </div>   </div>  </div></li></ul><p></p><p></p>'),
(73, 81, 'en', 'Focusing Ideas', 'Focusing Ideas', '<p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Using Affinity Mapping to Ideate</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Earlier we used&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">affinity mapping</em>&nbsp;to build themes from our research data. Now we\'ll look at how we can use it to&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">ideate</em>&nbsp;and to&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">focus our ideas</em>.</p> </div>   </div>  </p><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/SslXzxuolCo\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Ultimately,\r\n our goal will be to take many ideas and narrow them down to just a few.\r\n Affinity mapping is a natural fit for this, because it allows us to see\r\n if we have ideas that have a similar theme (e.g., all ideas around \r\nproviding weather information). Once we see which ideas cluster together\r\n into a theme, we\'ll be able to combine the best qualities of those \r\nideas to create one high-quality idea.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">This technique makes the most sense when ideating in groups where many people might independently arrive at similar ideas.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Notice\r\n that this is also a great example of how we can mold the techniques in \r\nthis course to fit whatever design challenge we\'re facing.</p> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">&nbsp;</h2> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Collaborative Ideation: Dot Voting</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/W4e0za7tM-k\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\"><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;You\'ll also often see dot voting referred to as&nbsp;<strong>dotmocracy</strong>&nbsp;(this is just another word for exactly the same process).</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\">&nbsp;</h4> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\">&nbsp;</h4> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\">Danger of Dot Voting</h4> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">When using dot voting, be wary of&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herd_behavior\" target=\"_blank\">herd behavior</a>—where\r\n people in a group think or behave differently than they would as \r\nindividuals. This can come up in behavioral studies (such as focus \r\ngroups) where many people might verbally agree with a statement said in a\r\n group conversation, even though they individually do not&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">actually</em>&nbsp;agree with the statement.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">In\r\n our context, the first person who places dots might bias the group\'s \r\nthinking. If they feel especially strongly about a dot, they might run \r\nover and place the dot. Often it is a good idea to offer time for \r\neveryone to silently think about where they want to place dots before \r\nproviding the dots.</p> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\"><em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">The\r\n following graphic is some output from an affinity-mapping and \r\ndot-voting workshop. Everyone was allowed to place at most one of each \r\ndot. Use the graphic to answer the questions below.</em></p> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>'),
(74, 82, 'en', 'Understanding Scope', 'Understanding Scope', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/5Z4ThOSAmOo\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">How to \"De-Scope\"</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">When\r\n you\'re talking about scope in the context of engineering, there are a \r\nfew ways you can reduce the work or complexity of a task. You can:</p> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Use frameworks, packages, or open-source code.</strong>&nbsp;If a developer can reuse something that is already built, it becomes much more manageable.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Reduce expectations.</strong>&nbsp;If\r\n your system has a technical requirement, it may be possible to relax \r\nthat requirement to reduce the scope. For example, there might be a \r\nspecification for the time it takes to complete a particular \r\ncomputation. Making this required time longer may make the task easier. \r\nThis also applies to things like accuracy (percentage of the time the \r\nsystem will be correct) or throughput (the number of concurrent requests\r\n or number of users).</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Not do the thing.</strong>&nbsp;Sometimes the best option is simply to find an alternative solution or feature.</li></ul> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Identifying \"Rat-Holes\"</h3> Sometimes\r\n when it is unclear how complex a task is, an engineer might recommend \r\ntrying a few experiments to see what things are possible. And in the \r\nnext meeting, they might propose more experiments, followed by more \r\nexperiments… and this cycle can continue forever. Try to identify when a\r\n scope might lead to this type of time-consuming exploration so you can \r\ncatch it early and determine if there are alternative paths.<p></p>'),
(75, 83, 'en', 'Prioritizing Features: Value vs. Complexity', 'Prioritizing Features: Value vs. Complexity', '<ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h1 class=\"chakra-heading css-1ank31f\">Prioritizing Features: Value vs Complexity Quadrants</h1> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Value vs Complexity Quadrants</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/5jNLZ_S__GU\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Prioritizing Features using the Quadrants</h2> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"vds-loading vds-loading--md\"> <div class=\"vds-loading__children\"> <div class=\"_1UN_ejel6QzQCa_M5Nn4bu\"> <div class=\"_2lGVVA99VY-snhn6dzPP-z\"> <div class=\"_3h3jXAJ1HmC2_sa49itKME _2nvHtsDYiD14gMJ8MpUp2c\">&nbsp;<iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/YsMuz3qaayk\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></div><div class=\"_3h3jXAJ1HmC2_sa49itKME _2nvHtsDYiD14gMJ8MpUp2c\"><em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Use the following graphic to answer the quiz</em>:</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>   </div> </li></ul><p></p>'),
(76, 84, 'en', 'Prioritizing Features: Score Matrix', 'Prioritizing Features: Score Matrix', '<h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Setting up the Matrix</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/YTc7sEqJSuY\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p><br></p><h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Prioritizing Features Using the Matrix</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/_76P-2fR35M\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p><br></p><ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">You can get your own copy of the feature prioritization matrix Gabe showed in the video&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/12qYb4fS2W99x5mQyWinHgNeMpErpHNbRjBynKVx1Xa8/copy\" target=\"_blank\">by making a copy of this Google sheet</a>&nbsp;or downloading this .xlsx version:&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://view.officeapps.live.com/op/view.aspx?src=https%3A%2F%2Fvideo.udacity-data.com%2Ftopher%2F2021%2FJuly%2F6100c12d_feature-prioritization-matrix-template%2Ffeature-prioritization-matrix-template.xlsx&amp;wdOrigin=BROWSELINK\" target=\"_blank\">Feature Prioritization Matrix Template</a>.</p> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Choosing Our Weights<span></span></h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">When\r\n we select weights for our columns, there is no hard rule - you should \r\nallow the conversation to organically assign points to criteria. \r\nHowever, you should aim to keep all of the weights within the same \r\nballpark so no single criterion completely dominates the others. One \r\napproach to solve this problem is to choose a fixed number of points and\r\n distribute those points across your criteria.</p> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">The Math Behind The Score</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Ideally,\r\n we\'ll want to be able to use the 1 (low) to 5 (high) for both Values \r\nand Costs. To accomplish this goal, we can transform our scores for our \r\nvalues simply by dividing by the maximum value (5). However, we want our\r\n costs to have the inverse effect - where a high value adds a smaller \r\namount to our score. This adds a little bit of complexity to the score \r\ncomputation, but it avoids negative numbers. By keeping all of our \r\nscores positive, we avoid bias if we\'re building something that has a \r\nvery high relative cost. In other words, decision-makers may use 0 as an\r\n arbitrary threshold and reject any proposed features less than zero. We\r\n can avoid this by transforming our costs by subtracting the score from \r\nthe maximum value (5) before dividing by 5. We can then use these \r\nadjusted scores multiplied by our weight to produce our weighted score. \r\nWe can sum all of these weighted scores to give us our final feature \r\nscore. Although the ranking is mathematically equivalent, it is \r\npsychologically perceived as different!</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">This math is described in the figure below:</p> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\">&nbsp;</div> </div> </div>   </div>   </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">    <div class=\"zls-blocks-image zw-txt-al-c\">  <img alt=\"images\" src=\"https://download.zoho.com/webdownload?x-service=ZohoLearn&amp;event-id=6352450000000132011&amp;x-cli-msg=%7B%22scopeID%22%3A%226352450000000004002%22%2C%22attachmentItemType%22%3A%22LESSON%22%2C%22isInline%22%3A%22true%22%2C%22courseId%22%3A%226352450000000008045%22%7D\" id=\"6352450000000132011\" style=\"min-height:\'100px\'\">  </div>     </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <p><em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Use the following matrix to answer the question:</em></p> </div>   </div>   </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">    <div class=\"zls-blocks-image zw-txt-al-c\">  <img alt=\"images\" src=\"https://download.zoho.com/webdownload?x-service=ZohoLearn&amp;event-id=6352450000000135001&amp;x-cli-msg=%7B%22scopeID%22%3A%226352450000000004002%22%2C%22attachmentItemType%22%3A%22LESSON%22%2C%22isInline%22%3A%22true%22%2C%22courseId%22%3A%226352450000000008045%22%7D\" id=\"6352450000000135001\" style=\"min-height:\'100px\'\">  </div>     </div> </li></ul>       <p></p><p><br></p><p></p><p></p>'),
(77, 85, 'en', 'Managing MVP Scope', 'Managing MVP Scope', '<p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h1 class=\"chakra-heading css-1ank31f\">Managing Minimum Viable Product Scope</h1> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Why Aim for \"Minimum\"?</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/PMp0LF7bTHY\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p><br></p><h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Piecemeal MVP</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/o-qrH_6S4f0\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Piecemeal Isn\'t Forever</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">When implementing a&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">piecemeal</em>&nbsp;strategy, it is important to realize these decisions are not permanent. Instead, we\'re trying to build as little as we can&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">today</em>&nbsp;to\r\n justify investment in the weeks to come. Although we\'ll be investing \r\nless money up front, these services usually will cost more after launch.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">At\r\n some point, if the product is successful, your company might try to \r\noptimize profit by building some services that were previously \r\noutsourced to a vendor. As a product gains traction, you might outgrow a\r\n hacked-together solution and need more customized systems. For example,\r\n you might need a specific weather model for a high-value customer.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">In\r\n sum, you might hack together a solution using piecemeal off-the-shelf \r\nparts today, and then revisit the investment decision later after the \r\nproduct as a whole has been de-risked.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">&nbsp;</p> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Concierge MVP</h2> </div>   </div>  <iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/5vhkxe2SNy0\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe><p><br></p><p> </p><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Concierge is Hard</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Before jumping into a&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">concierge</em>&nbsp;MVP\r\n consider if the solution can be achieved by a human. The example of a \r\ntrip interruption advisor still might need some technology built to \r\naccomplish the task. For example, they will need to have some interface \r\nto see flight statuses or weather. The key here is that it is easier to \r\nbuild a complex interface and train a human to interpret the information\r\n than it is to build a simple interface and train a machine to interpret\r\n information for our user.<span></span></p> </div>   </div>   </div>      </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>'),
(78, 86, 'en', 'Lesson Review', 'Lesson Review', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/K55WJSOXedY\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p> </p><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">What we\'ve learned</h2> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">A technique called&nbsp;<strong>Affinity Mapping</strong>&nbsp;for taking research and promoting themes on which to focus our efforts.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Structured opportunity definition using the&nbsp;<strong>How Might We</strong>&nbsp;style question prompt.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Techniques to Ideate when we have creativity block including&nbsp;<strong>Crazy-8</strong>&nbsp;Sketching,&nbsp;<strong>Bad Idea</strong>&nbsp;Sketching, and&nbsp;<strong>Combinatorics</strong>.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">How to ask good questions to engineers to understand&nbsp;<strong>feature scope</strong>.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Techniques for prioritizing features for qualitative (<strong>Quadrants</strong>) and quantitative (<strong>Matrix</strong>) stakeholders.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">What a&nbsp;<strong>Minimum Viable Product</strong>&nbsp;is and why it\'s a good thing to build</li></ul> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">What we\'ll learn next:&nbsp;<strong>User Interface Principles</strong></h2> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Common design patterns for mobile and web application interfaces.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">How much detail we need in order to collect information on product value.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Ways we can improve the accessibility of our designs so they\'re usable for more people, including people with disabilities.</li></ul> </div>   </div>   </div>'),
(79, 87, 'en', 'What is a User Interface?', 'What is a User Interface?', '<div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h1 class=\"chakra-heading css-1ank31f\">What is a User Interface (UI)?</h1> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">A&nbsp;<strong>User Interface (UI)</strong>&nbsp;is a way in which a user can interact with a product. In our context, we\'re talking about&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">digital</em>&nbsp;interfaces—specifically,\r\n digitally interfaces for mobile apps (that run on smartphones) or web \r\napps (that typically run in a web browser).</p><p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/jJwoyP4iETA\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">To build a strong UI, we start by considering the problems and insights we\'ve learned from our&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">research synthesis</em>. We then build \"realistic solutions\" which the user would be able to interact with to solve their problems.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">As we\'re building interfaces, we often have additional&nbsp;<strong>design constraints</strong>—things that limit what we can implement.</p> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">A&nbsp;<strong>design constraint</strong>&nbsp;is a characteristic of the interface that limits what we can implement.</p> </blockquote> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">These include things like the&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">device type</em>&nbsp;and thus the&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">screen characteristics</em>.\r\n For example, it is very different designing an interface where the user\r\n taps on a small iPhone screen than it is designing an interface where a\r\n user clicks around on a large desktop monitor.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Thus,\r\n the optimal design solution for a particular interface may depend on \r\nthe particular constraints we\'re dealing with. Fortunately, there are \r\nalready many known&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">design patterns</em>&nbsp;out there.</p> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">A&nbsp;<strong>design pattern</strong>&nbsp;is a general solution that can be applied to a particular type of problem.</p> </blockquote> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Design\r\n patterns for many common design constraints have already been worked \r\nout. In this lesson, we\'ll explore design patterns that make sense for \r\nboth of the application types we described above (both mobile and \r\ndesktop interfaces).</p> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">UX vs UI vs UX/UI</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">We\'re\r\n crossing an important boundary at this stage. Up until now, we\'ve been \r\nbuilding an understanding, making key decisions about our design \r\nstrategy, and trying to figure out which features are most valuable to \r\nour users. We\'ve been talking about our product in an abstract way that \r\nmight not even be software.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">In other words, we\'ve been focusing on the&nbsp;<strong>User Experience (UX)</strong>&nbsp;of\r\n our product. UX is a critical skill to build as a designer. It focuses \r\non answering the \"why\" of building a specific product. Mastery of UX \r\nskills will yield high impact on the products you ship.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">But now we\'ll be focusing on the \"what\". The&nbsp;<strong>User Interface (UI)</strong>&nbsp;is\r\n how we\'ll solve the problems we know we need based on our UX research. \r\nThe UI we\'re describing assumes we\'re building a digital software \r\nproduct. It focuses on layouts, pixels, and user flows.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">UI is also important to building successful products, as without it users will not enjoy what you build.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">In practice as a designer, you\'ll often find yourself gravitating towards UX&nbsp;<strong>or</strong>&nbsp;UI\r\n depending on your skills, interest, and your team\'s needs. However, in \r\nmany companies, you\'ll find these roles are blurred together into a \r\nUX/UI designer who is responsible for the total user experience.</p> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Lesson Overview</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">In this lesson, we\'ll be learning&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\"><strong>User Interface (UI)</strong></em>&nbsp;principles, including:</p> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Common design patterns for mobile and web application interfaces.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">How much detail we need in order to collect information on product value.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Ways we can improve the accessibility of our designs so they\'re usable for more people, including people with disabilities.</li></ul> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><p></p>'),
(80, 88, 'en', 'Understanding Fidelity', 'Understanding Fidelity', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/kWkcCf9PBWc\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Leaving Out Information</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Every\r\n piece of information that is included in a prototype requires a \r\ndecision. If you later change your mind, you\'ll need to go through the \r\ndesign and make changes to these elements throughout your prototype. \r\nInstead, at this phase of design you\'ll want to move fast. Leaving out \r\nsome more detailed information will allow you to design for the bigger \r\npicture without spending too much time on details for screens that may \r\nnot even end up in your prototype. Some things you should consider \r\nomitting from your design at this stage are:</p> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Color</strong>&nbsp;–\r\n It\'s often best to design in black and white first. You\'ll usually find\r\n yourself fixating on how colors work together or if they are on-brand \r\nfor your company. If you don\'t use color, you don\'t have these problems.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Fake or Real Data</strong>&nbsp;–\r\n It takes time to think of fake company names or wrangle example data \r\ninto a format that you can use in designs. You might find yourself \r\ntrying to come up with realistic information for things like names or \r\ngraphs only to find you don\'t need that information.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Animation</strong>&nbsp;–\r\n Animations are a great way to provide feedback to users and optimize a \r\nUI. But at this stage we\'re not optimizing—we\'re building a baseline—and\r\n animations take time to perfect.</li></ul> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Communicating Fidelity</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">When\r\n you discuss fidelity with stakeholders, it is critical that you clearly\r\n communicate what you\'ll be delivering. It is not enough to simply state\r\n that you\'re \"working on a Low-Fidelity prototype\". Even worse, the \r\nphrase \"Low-Fidelity\" is often shortened to&nbsp;<strong>Lo-Fi</strong>. This\r\n could mean different things to different people—and they may be \r\ndisappointed if the resulting designs are simple shapes with limited \r\ncolor.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">To avoid such issues, focus\r\n on communicating why you\'re choosing to work in low-fidelity and what \r\nthe output may look like before you jump into the design. It is \r\nimportant to explain to stakeholders that although outputs might look \r\nsimple, it is often the case that the version they\'re seeing went \r\nthrough many rounds of iteration and refinement, all of which was \r\npossible&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">because</em>&nbsp;of the chosen fidelity.</p> </div>   </div>   </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Form Factors</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/Hb08HGZxY0Q\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Form Factors and Screens</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Most commonly, we\'ll be designing digital products for&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">screens</em>. It may seem obvious, but let\'s think about what that really means.</p> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">A&nbsp;<strong>screen</strong>&nbsp;is a device that is composed of small elements that produce colored light. Those elements are called&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel\" target=\"_blank\">pixels</a>. There are a finite number of pixels on a screen—and the number of pixels is known as the&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">resolution</em>.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Be\r\n aware that smaller screens don’t always mean lower resolutions. \r\nCellphone screens may be physically smaller, but the pixel density on \r\nsome of these screens is quite high, rivaling the number of pixels found\r\n in some large format TVs!</p> </blockquote> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">As\r\n you’re choosing a form factor for low-fidelity prototypes it’s \r\nimportant to try to answer the question, \"Which screen will a majority \r\nof my users be using?”. You’ll find in practice that there are many \r\ndifferent screens, but you should start designing for the most \r\ncommon—and then you can tweak and tune your designs later.</p> </div>   </div>   </div>   </div>  </div></li></ul><p></p>'),
(81, 89, 'en', 'Finding Design Inspiration', 'Finding Design Inspiration', '<p><h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Searching for UI Elements</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/_lnZmXz5hBM\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\">Share your work!</h4> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">As\r\n you build a portfolio and a personal brand as a designer, you\'ll want \r\nto consider using some of the sites mentioned in the video (like&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://dribbble.com/\" target=\"_blank\">dribble</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://behance.net/\" target=\"_blank\">behance</a>)\r\n to share your work with potential employers. These networks are great \r\nnot only for finding inspiration, but also for sharing inspiration. The \r\ndesign community is welcoming and offers a ton of opportunity to \r\nhighlight your skills as you build them!</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">&nbsp;</p> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Design Frameworks</h2> </div>   </div>  <iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/LeF280WL1YE\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe><p><br></p><p> </p></p><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\">Choosing a Design Framework<span></span></h4> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">In this video, Gabe introduces&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://material-ui.com/\" target=\"_blank\">material-ui.com</a>. However, this is far from the only option. There are many popular and well-maintained UI libraries to choose from (<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://www.skysilk.com/blog/2018/6-best-css-frameworks-2019/\" target=\"_blank\">here are six popular examples</a>).\r\n Before you design, you should have a conversation with your engineers \r\nabout which framework would work best with the team\'s technical \r\ncapabilities—and share which framework you think has the best components\r\n for your project.</p> </div>   </div>   </div>             <p><p></p></p>');
