(104, 112, 'en', 'Logistics', 'Logistics', '<h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Recruiting Current Users</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/dtKxplhsnUQ\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Where to Conduct Your Session</h2> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Conference Rooms</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">The\r\n best option (and maybe an obvious one) for where to conduct a usability\r\n study is in a quiet conference room. This will give you privacy to have\r\n a deep conversation with your respondent, free from distractions. \r\nConference rooms are great if you\'re recording the session because they \r\nwill be free from background noise that might make listening to the \r\nsession challenging.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Sometimes you\r\n might not have access to a private room—like if you\'re working for a \r\nstartup without an office or are conducting research away from where \r\nyour company is based. In these cases, if you have the budget you can \r\ncheck to see if you can reserve a conference room in a&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">coworking space</em>. A few solid options for conference rooms that can be booked hourly in many cities around the world are&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://wework.com/\" target=\"_blank\">WeWork</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"http://breather.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Breather</a>.</p> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Coffee Shops</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Although\r\n it\'s not the best choice due to noise and lack of privacy, running a \r\nsession in a coffee shop will work in a pinch. If you have no option for\r\n a formal coworking space, a quiet cafe is often a perfectly acceptable \r\nplace to conduct a usability session. If you choose this option, you \r\nmight want to get to the coffee shop early to ensure you have space. And\r\n you may want to scope out a few coffee shops in your city to see which \r\nyou can rely on to have solid wifi and be relatively quiet.</p> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">The Respondent\'s Home or Office</h3> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Often\r\n you\'ll get tremendous insight when visiting a respondent\'s natural \r\nsetting. You might observe how they organize their space or what things \r\nthey keep around their workspace. If you\'re able to travel, asking to \r\nrun a session in a respondent\'s home or office is a great way to \r\nstrengthen your empathy with the user, while giving you a suitable space\r\n to run the session.</p> </div>   </div>  <p><br></p><p></p>'),
(105, 113, 'en', 'Remote Usability Sessions', 'Remote Usability Sessions', '<p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Video Conferencing Sessions</h2> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">&nbsp;</h2> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Zoom Setup</h2><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/r0jRYt6s12Q\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Sharing Screens</h2> </div> </div> </div> </div>     <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">You\r\n usually have a limited amount of time with respondents and you want to \r\nminimize the probability of technical glitches. I\'ve recently realized \r\nthat sharing my screen usually has fewer hiccups when starting the \r\nsession. This is because there is no requirement to try to guide your \r\nuser to the buttons to share their screen, and then you might have to \r\nshare links, prototypes, or other designs with them. All of these steps \r\nintroduce possible confusion where you can\'t step in to help.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Zoom offers great support to share your screen and even computer control with a respondent. You can&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/201362153-How-Do-I-Share-My-Screen-\" target=\"_blank\">read detailed instructions on the zoom support docs</a>.</p> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">&nbsp;</h2> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Example Usability Session<span></span></h2> </div> </div> </div> </div>     <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Download the usability guide and follow along with the following video:&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NUrRbhKBtckPvxnXGjuZq0t_uWjPizWaxUwn1ghEWWY/copy\" target=\"_blank\">Google doc</a>,&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"http://udacity.github.io/UXND/lofi/UsabilityGuide-UdacityAir.docx\" target=\"_blank\">docx</a>,&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"http://udacity.github.io/UXND/lofi/UsabilityGuide-UdacityAir.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">pdf</a></p>..</div><div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/xvSuMLgUQgk\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>'),
(106, 114, 'en', 'Digital Journey Map (Miro)', 'Digital Journey Map (Miro)', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/-PeYwRwUl9A\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p> </p><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\"><em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Power In Numbers</em>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Diminishing Returns</em>?</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">We\'ve\r\n discussed in this course how certain stakeholders will be more \r\nimpressed by numbers. If they have a statistics background, they may \r\nfeel the need to have large robust studies with many respondents.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">In\r\n design, we often don\'t need this kind of scale. Often in UX research, \r\nthere is a magic number of respondents where we\'ll start to see \r\nrepeating behaviors—usually this happens with about&nbsp;<strong>5 users</strong>.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">The thinking is:</p> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">The first user will be unique by definition.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">The second user might have a few similar behaviors or issues as the first.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">The third might have some overlapping behaviors as the first two.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">By the fifth user, we probably have seen most of the insightful behaviors.</li></ul> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">With\r\n additional users, we may simply start to see the same issues coming up \r\nover and over; thus, we\'ll begin to get diminishing returns on the time \r\nwe\'re investing.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">If you\'re interested, you can read more about this concept on the&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://www.invisionapp.com/inside-design/ux-usability-research-testing/\" target=\"_blank\">Invision Blog</a>.<span></span></p> </div>   </div>   </div>'),
(107, 115, 'en', 'Lesson Review', 'Lesson Review', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/1zmc99PI2jQ\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">What we\'ve learned:</h2> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Why it\'s important to test our designs before launch.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Different usability testing methodologies including&nbsp;<strong>moderated and un-moderated sessions</strong>.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">How to run a moderated usability session using a&nbsp;<strong>Usability Guide</strong>.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Helpful tips to use&nbsp;<strong>Zoom</strong>&nbsp;for remote moderated sessions.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Techniques for making sense of usability test results on our&nbsp;<strong>User Flow Diagram</strong>.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Examples on how to iterate your design based on feedback.</li></ul> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">What we\'ll do next:&nbsp;<strong>Demonstrate your skills in a Low-Fidelity Rapid Prototype Sprint 🙌🎉📈</strong></h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Next,\r\n you\'ll start the project where you\'ll implement all of the skills we\'ve\r\n covered in this course—from understanding research through to creating \r\nand testing prototypes!</p> </div>   </div>'),
(108, 116, 'en', 'Overview', 'Overview', '<div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Mastering Your Low-Fidelity Rapid Prototyping Skills!</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Your\r\n goal in this project is to demonstrate the skills we’ve covered in this\r\n course—starting with research synthesis and ending with a validated, \r\nlow-fidelity prototype.</p> </div> </div> </div> </div><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/TMjPImS1u8w\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></div><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Main parts of the project</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">The Project is broken up into three key sections:</p> <ol class=\"css-13a5a39\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Research Synthesis.</strong>&nbsp;You\'ll\r\n use user interviews to build your understanding of—and empathy \r\nfor—potential users. You\'ll exit this phase with feature ideas for your \r\nproduct. (Applying skills from the&nbsp;<code class=\"chakra-code css-p3l7io\">Define</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code class=\"chakra-code css-p3l7io\">Synthesis</code>&nbsp;lessons)</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Rapid Prototyping.</strong>&nbsp;Next,\r\n you\'ll apply your research understanding to see your ideas come to life\r\n in the form of interactive prototypes. You\'ll use paper and digital \r\ntechniques we\'ve covered in this course. (Applying skills from the&nbsp;<code class=\"chakra-code css-p3l7io\">UI Principles</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code class=\"chakra-code css-p3l7io\">Clickable Prototyping</code>&nbsp;lessons)</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\"><strong>Usability Study and Design Iteration.</strong>&nbsp;Finally,\r\n you\'ll validate your concepts and implementation by taking your designs\r\n into the wild in a short usability study. Your final task will be to \r\nimprove your design from what you learn from actual potential users. \r\n(Applying skills from the&nbsp;<code class=\"chakra-code css-p3l7io\">Usability Testing</code>&nbsp;lesson)</li></ol> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Throughout the process, you can refer to the&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://review.udacity.com/#!/rubrics/2670/view\" target=\"_blank\">project rubric</a>&nbsp;to see exactly what we\'ll be looking for when we review your project.</p> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Choose Your Path</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">This\r\n project will build on the research you did in the previous course. For \r\nthat course, you may have chosen to research the Coffee Shop app, or you\r\n may have come up with a different design problem that you were \r\ninterested in. You can make a similar choice here:</p> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\">If you chose the Coffee Shop app for the last project</h4> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">You\r\n can continue with the Coffee Shop problem here. You can use the \r\nresearch you\'ve already done for the last course, plus we\'ll provide \r\nsome additional pre-recorded user interviews that you can use if you\'d \r\nlike to.</p> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\">If you chose your own topic for the last project</h4> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">You\r\n can continue with that topic here, drawing on your research from the \r\nlast course. Or, If you\'ve decided that your topic is too large and \r\ncomplex in scope and you&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">don\'t</em>&nbsp;want\r\n to use it for this project, you can still switch to the Coffee Shop \r\napp. In that case you won\'t have your own research, but we\'ll provide \r\nsome pre-recorded user interviews that you can use instead.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">You can find more details on the next two pages, called&nbsp;<strong>Option 1</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Option 2</strong>.</p> </div> </div> </div> </div>     <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Project Requirements</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Whichever path you choose, your project must:</p> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Design a digital product for a mobile application or a web application (your choice!)</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Follow the design principles and accessibility tips described in this course</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Include a complete digital user experience that is tied to values uncovered in research</li></ul> As\r\n you\'re exploring directions for your project, try to keep scope top of \r\nmind. You should aim to be implementing only 2–3 features, where each \r\nfeature includes a user flow of a few screens that each contain \r\ncomponents. Ultimately, you will decide the feature set of your \r\ndesign—it\'s ok to “rip the brief” and expand the project definition a \r\nlittle bit to explore some creative opportunities. But keep in mind, if \r\nyour ideas or features are too complex, you may have a hard time \r\ncompleting the project on time. Take breaks, go for walks, and think \r\nthrough each step of the project to make sure that the direction you’re \r\nmoving in is strong, but manageable.</div><p></p>'),
(109, 117, 'en', 'Option 1: Udacity Coffee Shop', 'Option 1: Udacity Coffee Shop', '<p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">The Design Problem</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Udacity\r\n is considering opening a digitally-enabled coffee shop experience. As \r\npart of this experience, students will be able to use an app (mobile or \r\nweb-based), which exists separately from the Udacity classroom, to \r\nperform actions such as:</p> <ul class=\"css-19qh3zo\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Placing their drink orders</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Collaborating with other students in the cafe</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Motivating progress on a Nanodegree</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Facilitating a productive study environment</li></ul> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">It\r\n is up to you to choose specific features that you want to implement, \r\nbut they must address one or more of these core design needs.</p> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Your Goal</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Your goal in this project is to:</p> <ol class=\"css-13a5a39\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Gather insights on drink-ordering behavior from user interviews, and then...</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Use these insights to create validated low-fidelity product concepts for the drink-ordering app</li></ol> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">There\r\n are many different ways to create a drink-ordering experience, and many\r\n different features of the app you could look into. For example, you \r\nmight want to look into what features of the drink-ordering experience \r\nare important to students. Or you might want to investigate what sort of\r\n collaboration features users are interested in.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">After\r\n watching the user interviews (below), you\'ll want to focus on a few \r\nareas to design, in order to narrow the scope of your research synthesis\r\n and then implement these designs in Figma.</p> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\"><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;As\r\n we mentioned on the previous page, you can use this topic for your \r\nprototyping regardless of whether you chose it as the design problem for\r\n the last project. If you worked on something else previously, we\'ve \r\nprovided user interviews (below) that you can use here. If you do have \r\nyour own interviews from the last project, you can use those and/or the \r\nones provided below (whatever you prefer).</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Interviews and Discussion Guide</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">You can use the semi-structured interviews below for your research synthesis.</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">The interviews were conducted using&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://udacity.github.io/UXND/lofi/InterviewDiscussionGuide-UdacityCafe.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">this discussion guide</a>.</p> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">&nbsp;</h3> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">&nbsp;</h3> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Coffee Shop Interview #1</h3><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/slD4fXZ-9Dw\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Coffee Shop Interview #2</h3><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/UIleJxwe3NA\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><p><br></p><h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Coffee Shop Interview #3</h3><p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/C2bdwQaOOK8\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe><br></p><p></p><p></p> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>'),
(110, 118, 'en', 'Option 2: Unique Topic', 'Option 2: Unique Topic', '<p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">In\r\n the project you did for the first course in this Nanodegree, you may \r\nhave chosen your own research topic. You\'re welcome to continue with \r\nthat topic here! This may be more challenging than using the pre-defined\r\n design problem (the Coffee Shop App), because you will be making more \r\ndecisions and are responsible for everything from scoping the work to \r\nchoosing the creative direction. But you\'ll also have a more unique \r\nproject in the end, which you could build into a strong portfolio piece.</p> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\">Design Brief</h4> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">You should start by writing a&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">brief</em>&nbsp;that describes the design problem. We’ve included a template paragraph you can use:</p> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">[Stakeholder]\r\n is considering doing [action]. As part of this product, [user] will be \r\nable to do [job(s)] so that they can achieve [outcome].</p> </blockquote> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Your\r\n brief should be broad and include a few key design options you’d like \r\nto explore. As you move through the sprint, allow this brief to \r\nexpand—but keep scope in mind at each stage to ensure you’re not \r\novercommitting.</p> </div>   </div>'),
(111, 119, 'en', 'Step 1: Research Synthesis', 'Step 1: Research Synthesis', '<ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <p>It\'s time to start your design sprint! The first step will be to get your Miro board set up.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">By the end of this sprint, your Miro board will be a single presentation of all your design artifacts:</h2> </div>   </div>   </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">    <div class=\"zls-blocks-image zw-txt-al-c\">  <img alt=\"images\" src=\"https://download.zoho.com/webdownload?x-service=ZohoLearn&amp;event-id=6352450000000134003&amp;x-cli-msg=%7B%22scopeID%22%3A%226352450000000004002%22%2C%22attachmentItemType%22%3A%22LESSON%22%2C%22isInline%22%3A%22true%22%2C%22courseId%22%3A%226352450000000008045%22%7D\" id=\"6352450000000134003\" style=\"min-height:\'100px\'\">  </div>     </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <p style=\"text-align: center\">Final Miro Board Layout</p> <p style=\"text-align: center\">&nbsp;</p> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"copy-length css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\"><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;In\r\n this next video, Gabe refers to interview videos \"below\". These are the\r\n Coffee Shop interviews that you should use if you\'ve chosen that topic \r\nfor your project, and they have been moved to the page above called&nbsp;<strong>Option 1: Udacity Coffee Shop</strong>. If you\'re going with your own topic, then you should reference your own interviews instead.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"> <div class=\"css-u8svcc\"> <div class=\"vds-loading vds-loading--md\"> <div class=\"vds-loading__children\"> <div class=\"_1UN_ejel6QzQCa_M5Nn4bu\"> <div class=\"_2lGVVA99VY-snhn6dzPP-z\"> <div class=\"_3h3jXAJ1HmC2_sa49itKME _2nvHtsDYiD14gMJ8MpUp2c\">&nbsp;</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>   </div>  </div><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/-k0mDCwLvlI\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></div><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <p>By the end of this step, you should have a complete Miro frame that looks like the following layout:</p> </div>   </div>   </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">    <div class=\"zls-blocks-image zw-txt-al-c\">  <img alt=\"images\" src=\"https://download.zoho.com/webdownload?x-service=ZohoLearn&amp;event-id=6352450000000135003&amp;x-cli-msg=%7B%22scopeID%22%3A%226352450000000004002%22%2C%22attachmentItemType%22%3A%22LESSON%22%2C%22isInline%22%3A%22true%22%2C%22courseId%22%3A%226352450000000008045%22%7D\" id=\"6352450000000135003\" style=\"min-height:\'100px\'\">  </div>     </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">&nbsp;</p> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\"><span></span>Select\r\n 3 features and mark each of them using a note of a different color. In \r\neach note, include text that describes the reason that the feature is \r\nimportant. The reasons should be based on the data you synthesized from \r\nthe interviews.</p> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">NOTE:\r\n This is a good checkpoint to sanity check the scope of your project. \r\nThink about if you cannot think of a large number of feature ideas \r\nbefore prioritizing, or you are struggling to prioritize features. If \r\neither of these questions are true, you might want to loop back to your \r\nnotes or synthesis steps to try to diverge further or focus based on \r\nyour research.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div>   </div> </li></ul>       </div></li></ul><p></p>'),
(112, 120, 'en', 'Step 2: Rapid Prototyping', 'Step 2: Rapid Prototyping', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/mvID4Cpqgvw\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">  <div class=\"zls-blocks-video zw-pos-re zw-index-none \">   <div class=\"zls-iframe-wrapper zls-video-element\">    </div>    </div> </div> <br></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <p>By\r\n the end of this step, you\'ll be adding two frames to your Miro board. \r\nThese frames should look something like the following (keeping in mind \r\nthat your board should include more sketches and detailed digital \r\nscreens):</p> </div>   </div>   </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">    <div class=\"zls-blocks-image zw-txt-al-c\">  <img alt=\"images\" src=\"https://download.zoho.com/webdownload?x-service=ZohoLearn&amp;event-id=6352450000000132019&amp;x-cli-msg=%7B%22scopeID%22%3A%226352450000000004002%22%2C%22attachmentItemType%22%3A%22LESSON%22%2C%22isInline%22%3A%22true%22%2C%22courseId%22%3A%226352450000000008045%22%7D\" id=\"6352450000000132019\" style=\"min-height:\'100px\'\">  </div></div></li></ul><p></p>'),
(113, 121, 'en', 'Step 3: Usability Study and Design Iteration', 'Step 3: Usability Study and Design Iteration', '<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/38vyol0qk3Y\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\"></iframe></p><ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <p>By\r\n the end of this step, you\'ll be adding two new frames to your Miro \r\nboard. These frames should look something like the following:</p> </div>   </div>   </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">    <div class=\"zls-blocks-image zw-txt-al-c\">  <img alt=\"images\" src=\"https://download.zoho.com/webdownload?x-service=ZohoLearn&amp;event-id=6352450000000133585&amp;x-cli-msg=%7B%22scopeID%22%3A%226352450000000004002%22%2C%22attachmentItemType%22%3A%22LESSON%22%2C%22isInline%22%3A%22true%22%2C%22courseId%22%3A%226352450000000008045%22%7D\" id=\"6352450000000133585\" style=\"min-height:\'100px\'\">  </div>     </div> </li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"> <div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">   <div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-1yztwzy\">Usability Study Recruiting Message Template:</h3> <p>&nbsp;Hey everyone! I’m currently seeking participants for my final project usability study.</p> <p>I’m located in the {{YOUR_TIMEZONE}} timezone and can be available {{YOUR_AVAILABILITY}} for a call.</p> <p>The call should take around 30 minutes.&nbsp;</p> <p>Thank you!</p> <p>*Remember, you should only complete the usability study if you’ve already submitted a project.*</p> <p>&nbsp;</p></div></div></div></li></ul><p></p>'),
(114, 122, 'en', 'Submit project', 'Submit project', '<p>  </p><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\">   <div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"> <div class=\"chakra-stack css-1s3a09c\"> <h1 class=\"chakra-heading css-iuea7g\">Submit project</h1> </div> <div class=\"css-0\"> <div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"> <h1 class=\"chakra-heading css-1ank31f\">You\'ve Completed an Entire Process from Concept to Lo-Fi Prototype 🤩🕺💃👍</h1> <h2 class=\"chakra-heading css-lb1dt4\">Now you\'ll need to submit your design artifacts for review.</h2> <p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Remember,\r\n designing products is hard work and takes time. You\'ll need to continue\r\n honing your skill through practice and patience.</p> <blockquote class=\"css-12m1603\"> <h4 class=\"chakra-heading css-xozg3x\"><strong>Before submitting, double-check that:</strong></h4> </blockquote> <ol class=\"css-13a5a39\"><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Each item in the&nbsp;<a class=\"chakra-link css-otuu82\" href=\"https://review.udacity.com/#!/rubrics/2670/view\" target=\"_blank\">rubric</a>&nbsp;meets all the required specifications.</li><li class=\"css-cvpopp\">Any Miro, Figma, or Google Drive links have proper permissions for reviewers to view and comment.</li></ol> </div> </div> </div>   </div>'),
(115, 123, 'en', 'Assignment 1', 'Assignment 1', '<p>You are expected to complete these tasks in at most 72 hours. Take a screenshot of the application after you have installed it and send it to my email labelled Assignment 1.</p><p>\r\n</p><ol>\r\n<li>Install VSCode along with the plugins</li><li>\r\n<p>Visit&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.github.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Github</a>&nbsp;and create a github account if you do not have one.</p><p>Install Git on your machine.</p></li><li>Install&nbsp;<code>Python3.10</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>Python3.9</code>&nbsp;on your machine.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n</ol>'),
(116, 124, 'en', 'Assignment 1', 'Assignment 1', '<div class=\"zls-blocks-container\">\r\n<div class=\"zls-editor-block zw-blocks-col zw-b-col1 \">\r\n<div class=\"zw-block-content\">\r\n<div class=\"zw-para \">\r\n<h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-671zrp\">Quick design sketch</h3>\r\n<div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">\r\n<p>Imagine you are hired by Good Food Restaurant to design a food-ordering app.</p>\r\n<p>This app allows consumers to do the following actions:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Choose food</li>\r\n<li>Pay</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Take about&nbsp;<strong>30 mins</strong>&nbsp;to sketch out your solutions. Sketch one screen for choosing food and one screen for paying. The sketches do not need to look polished! The purpose of this exercise is not to prove that you have amazing design skills—it\'s just to get some experience with the process. We will then look at some of the things to consider when making a sketch like this.</p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p>Send a picture of the sketch to my email labelled Assignment 1.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div></div>'),
(117, 125, 'en', 'Assignment 2', 'Assignment 2', '<h3 class=\"chakra-heading css-671zrp\">Quick design sketch — Part 2</h3><p>\r\n</p><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">\r\n<p>Look at your sketch and see if you can come up with answers to these questions:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Who were you designing for?</li>\r\n<li>Who might not be a good fit for your design? Write your answers next to your sketch.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Now, revise your design. Will your design be different if the user is a frequent customer? A 5-year old child? Someone who only uses cash? A foreign traveler? I would like to see you sketch out some variations.</p><p>Send a picture of the sketch to my email labelled Assignment 2.</p></div>'),
(119, 127, 'en', 'Submit Your Design Problem', 'Submit Your Design Problem', '<div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">\r\n<p>It\'s time to select a topic! Use the guidelines below to select a topic and submit</p>\r\n<p>Guidelines:</p>\r\n</div><p>\r\n</p><div class=\"css-1pbf5mu\">\r\n<p><strong>Choose a broad domain</strong> for which you want to create a design. It could be anything of your choice, such as, vacations, plantation, environment, economy, technology, governance, etc.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Dissect your topic</strong>&nbsp;based on user segments or niche market; Go at least 4-6 levels deep, and consider using a diagram (like the one above) to visualize possible users and subjects you could target</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">\r\n<p>As you consider topics, here are some specific questions to ask yourself to make sure you\'ve got a reasonable scope and a good topic. Don\'t move on with the project until you feel each of these statements is true about your topic:</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"css-1pbf5mu\">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"css-m4qchi\">\r\n<div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The topic targets&nbsp;<strong>a specific type of user</strong>. This should be a group of users who all share the same need or problem. Be as specific as possible (i.e., \"language-learners\" is too broad; a specific group like \"adults with full-time jobs who are learning a language for fun\" would be better).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"css-m4qchi\">\r\n<div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>You can conveniently&nbsp;<strong>reach out to your target users</strong>&nbsp;and recruit a significant number of them to participate in your study. When thinking of your target user, try to make it concrete, to be sure you can actually reach the people you\'ll need to recruit. Can you contact them directly through email or phone? Or can you get that contact information through someone you have a direct connection with?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"css-m4qchi\">\r\n<div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The topic focuses on&nbsp;<strong>a single task flow</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"css-m4qchi\">\r\n<div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The topic is something&nbsp;<strong>you can research with the time and resources you have</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div></div>');
INSERT INTO `text_lesson_translations` (`id`, `text_lesson_id`, `locale`, `title`, `summary`, `content`) VALUES
(120, 128, 'en', 'Select Your Design Problem', 'Select Your Design Problem', '<ul class=\"zls-ul-reset zls-blocks-wrapper zw-fl-grow\"><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><div class=\"css-1pbf5mu\"><ul class=\"css-1m3y3vl\"><li class=\"css-0\"></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"><div class=\"css-u8svcc\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><h1>Select Your Design Problem</h1></div></div></div><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"><div class=\"css-u8svcc\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>It\'s time to think about what you want to do for your final project! The first step is to choose a problem or need that you\'re interested in solving for. This could be essentially anything you like, as long as it can be addressed by an application (specifically, an app that could run on mobile phone or web platforms).</p><p>In choosing the overall design space, you have two general options: You can either select a predefined problem (Option 1) or choose your own (Option 2).</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><h3>Option 1: The Udacity Coffee Shop app</h3><p>Udacity is considering opening a digitally-enabled coffee shop experience. As part of this experience, students will be able to use an app (mobile or web-based), which exists separately from the Udacity classroom, to perform actions such as:</p><ul><li>Placing their drink orders</li><li>Collaborating with other students in the coffee shop</li><li>Motivating progress on a Nanodegree</li><li>Facilitating a productive study environment</li></ul></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><p>It is up to you to choose specific features that you want to implement, but they must address one or more of these core design needs.</p><p>This option will be a little easier, in the sense that the problem space has already been defined for you—although you\'ll still need to narrow down on a specific aspect of that problem space. On the other hand, you will be tackling the same problem as many of your fellow students, so your project will not be as unique as if you go with Option 2.</p></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><h3>Option 2: Select your own design problem</h3><p>Find a problem space that you are interested in. Is there an application you wish you had, but that does not yet exist? It can be about pretty much anything—such as vacation planning, a dry cleaning pick-up service, or a comic book trading platform.</p></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><p>Selecting your own design problem is a little more challenging, but it has a few benefits. First, the process of selecting a good problem is itself an important skill to have as a UX designer, so this will give you additional practice with that skill. And second, you\'ll generate a project that is totally unique, and that no other students have done. This can potentially be developed into a strong portfolio piece—so if creating an awesome portfolio piece is one of your goals, then selecting your own problem might be the way to go.</p></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><h2>Scoping the topic</h2><p>Whichever option you go with, you\'ll still need to narrow in on a specific aspect of the problem. One of the biggest risks in tackling a design problem is choosing a problem that is too big. Especially when you have limited time and resources (like you do for this project), it\'s important to land on a topic that has an appropriate scope and won\'t become overwhelming or impossible to get done.</p></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><h4>Example</h4><p>Here\'s an example of the decision process for selecting a topic and narrowing the scope. At each step, we make a choice about which option we want to pursue (the chosen options are shown here in italics).</p><ol><li><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">Choose a domain/industry</span><ul><li><em>Food ordering</em>, online learning, buying shoes online, etc.</li></ul></li><li><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">Choose a more niche market</span><ul><li>Food ordering →&nbsp;<em>ordering pizza from a pizza chain</em></li></ul></li><li><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">Choose a user group (only one)</span><ul><li>Who are the users of a pizza ordering app?<ul><li>Chefs who need to track incoming orders</li><li>Pizza delivery man</li><li>Store managers who want to see sales</li><li><em>Customers</em></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">Narrow down the users</span><ul><li>Office managers who buy 20 pizzas for a company party</li><li>People who want to eat pizza inside the pizza shop</li><li><em>College students who just want to order a pizza delivery</em></li></ul></li><li><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">Choose a single critical user journey</span><ul><li>Sign-up for the app</li><li>Set up payment</li><li><em>Choose a pizza</em></li><li>Check delivery time</li></ul></li></ol></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><p><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">The final scope:</span>&nbsp;<em>Design an app for college students to order pizza.</em></p><p>You\'ll want to go through a similar process for your project to narrow down the scope of your design problem. As you work on this, it may help to create a diagram showing possible users and subjects you could target. Below is an example, which I created with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://whimsical.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Whimsical.com</a>. You can use any tool you like for this process (e.g., digital tools, pen and paper, whiteboard, etc.).</p></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-image zw-txt-al-c\"><img alt=\"images\" src=\"https://download.zoho.com/webdownload?x-service=ZohoLearn&amp;event-id=6352450000000014003&amp;x-cli-msg=%7B%22scopeID%22%3A%226352450000000004002%22%2C%22attachmentItemType%22%3A%22LESSON%22%2C%22isInline%22%3A%22true%22%2C%22courseId%22%3A%226352450000000008045%22%7D\" id=\"6352450000000014003\"></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"><div class=\"css-u8svcc\"><div class=\"css-1dtn3on\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>It\'s time to select a topic! Here are the steps:</p></div><div class=\"css-1pbf5mu\"><br><p></p><div class=\"css-m4qchi\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>If you selected the Coffee Shop app, then this part is already done for you.</p></div></div><div class=\"css-m4qchi\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p><span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">Dissect your topic</span>&nbsp;based on user segments or niche market; Go at least 4-6 levels deep, and consider using a diagram (like the one above) to visualize possible users and subjects you could target</p></div></div><div class=\"css-m4qchi\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>Select a&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">specific, narrowly scoped design problem</span>&nbsp;that you want to tackle for your research project</p></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\"><div class=\"css-u8svcc\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \">&nbsp;</div></div></div></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"></div></div><br></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><h2>Is it do-able?</h2><p>The key is to find a design problem you are passionate about, but also take feasibility into consideration. Do you have access to the target users? For example, if you are interested in building a tool for rocket ships, you need to think about how many astronauts you can talk to. And is the problem specific enough? If the problem is too large, you may not have the time to do good research on it.</p></div></div></div></li><li class=\"\" style=\"padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;\"><div class=\"zls-blocks-container\"><div class=\"zls-blocks zls-fixed-width:950 zls-fs17 zw-word-wrap zls-grid zls-gap20 zls-g-col1\"><div class=\"zls-tinymce-text-content \" data-placeholder=\"Good products come from good craftsmanship. They come from careful attention to design, from endless rounds of refinement, and iteration. But none of those things come easily.                       \"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>As you consider topics, here are some specific questions to ask yourself to make sure you\'ve got a reasonable scope and a good topic. Don\'t move on with the project until you feel each of these statements is true about your topic:</p></div><div class=\"css-1pbf5mu\"><ul class=\"css-1m3y3vl\"><li class=\"css-0\"><div class=\"css-m4qchi\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>The topic targets&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">a specific type of user</span>. This should be a group of users who all share the same need or problem. Be as specific as possible (i.e., \"language-learners\" is too broad; a specific group like \"adults with full-time jobs who are learning a language for fun\" would be better).</p></div></div></li><li class=\"css-0\"><div class=\"css-m4qchi\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>You can conveniently&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">reach out to your target users</span>&nbsp;and recruit a significant number of them to participate in your study. When thinking of your target user, try to make it concrete, to be sure you can actually reach the people you\'ll need to recruit. Can you contact them directly through email or phone? Or can you get that contact information through someone you have a direct connection with?</p></div></div></li><li class=\"css-0\"><div class=\"css-m4qchi\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>The topic focuses on&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">a single task flow</span>.</p></div></div></li><li class=\"css-0\"><div class=\"css-m4qchi\"><div class=\"_15vzQlp3FJ8f94suLiPCPf ureact-markdown \"><p>The topic is something&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: bolder;\">you can research with the time and resources you have</span>.</p></div></div></li><li class=\"css-0\"><br></li></ul></div></div></div></div></li></ul></div></div></div></div></li></ul>'),
(121, 129, 'en', 'Create Your Research Plan', 'Create Your Research Plan', '<p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\" style=\"color: rgb(36, 42, 66); font-family: LatoLatin, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\">Before moving on, you should get started on your research plan.</p><p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\" style=\"color: rgb(36, 42, 66); font-family: LatoLatin, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\">Use the template provided below.</p><p class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\" style=\"color: rgb(36, 42, 66); font-family: LatoLatin, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\">Once you\'ve created your document, see if you can fill out some of the info for the&nbsp;<em class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">interview study</em>. We\'ll get into the details about how to do an interview study next, so you don\'t have to get into all of the details now. But you should be able to at least draft the following:</p><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\" style=\"color: rgb(36, 42, 66); font-family: LatoLatin, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><div class=\"css-u8svcc\"><div class=\"css-1do9afp\"><div class=\"chakra-stack css-1ac1sc7\"><br><div class=\"ureact-markdown css-tc5hjw\"><ol><li class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Write the background</li><li class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Write the research goals</li><li class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Write the overarching research questions</li><li class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Write how and where you will recruit participants</li><li class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">If you are going to use a screener, write your screener questions (if you are recruiting friends and family, you can skip writing a screener—though even then, it would still be good practice!)</li><li class=\"chakra-text css-o3oz8b\">Write the introduction part of the script</li></ol></div></div></div></div></div><div class=\"css-1m96lhp\" style=\"color: rgb(36, 42, 66); font-family: LatoLatin, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><div class=\"css-u8svcc\">&nbsp;</div></div>'),
(122, 130, 'en', 'Assignment 2', 'Assignment 2', '<p><span style=\"color: rgb(36, 42, 66); font-family: LatoLatin, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\">Install Postgre SQL</span></p>'),
(123, 131, 'en', 'Assignment 2.5', 'Assignment 2.5', '<p><div class=\"zls-learner-answer-con zw-m-t40\" style=\"margin-top: 40px; color: rgb(36, 42, 66); font-family: LatoLatin, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\"></div></p><div class=\"zls-header-con zw-m-b20\" style=\"margin-bottom: 20px; color: rgb(36, 42, 66); font-family: LatoLatin, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\"><div class=\"zls-f-w600 zw-m-b5 zw-primary-txt-color\" style=\"font-weight: 600; color: var(--product-accent-color); margin-bottom: 5px;\">Question</div><div class=\"zls-fs16\" style=\"font-size: 1.6rem;\"><p style=\"margin-top: 0px;\">Consider the following project.</p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px;\">The company has been tasked with job of creating an ERP system. It contains the following modules:</p><ol><li>User Management</li><li>Finance</li><li>HR</li><li>Inventory</li></ol><p style=\"margin-top: 0px;\">Here is a break down of all the database models in each module:</p><ol><li><strong>USER MGT</strong><ol><li>User/Staff Account C.R.U.D.</li></ol></li><li><strong>FINANCE</strong><ol><li>Budget C.R.U.D</li><li>Invoice C.R.U.D</li><li>Accounts C.R.U.D</li><li>Orders C.R.U.D</li></ol></li><li><strong>HR</strong><ol><li>Department C.R.U.D</li><li>Leave Application C.R.U.D</li><li>Staff Query C.R.U.D</li><li>Recruitment C.R.U.D</li><li>Staff Performance Review C.R.U.D</li></ol></li><li><strong>Inventory</strong><ol><li>Item C.R.U.D</li><li>Audit Trail C.R.U.D</li></ol></li></ol><p style=\"margin-top: 0px;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px;\"><strong>Given the above modules, do the following:</strong></p><ol><li>Design a schema for each model in all the modules. For instance, the ITEM model in INVENTORY module may look like this:<br><pre class=\" language-javascript\" style=\"overflow: auto; margin: 0.5em 0px; line-height: 1.5; color: black; background: rgb(245, 242, 240); font-family: Consolas, Monaco, &quot;Andale Mono&quot;, &quot;Ubuntu Mono&quot;, monospace; font-size: 1em; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; tab-size: 4; hyphens: none; position: relative; padding: 1em; box-sizing: border-box; text-shadow: white 0px 1px; direction: ltr;\"><code class=\" language-javascript\" style=\"line-height: 1.5; color: black; background: linear-gradient(transparent 50%, rgba(69, 142, 209, 0.04) 50%) 0% 0% / 3em 3em local content-box rgb(253, 253, 253); font-family: Consolas, Monaco, &quot;Andale Mono&quot;, &quot;Ubuntu Mono&quot;, monospace; font-size: 1em; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; tab-size: 4; hyphens: none; max-height: inherit; height: inherit; padding: 0px 1em; display: block; overflow: auto; text-shadow: white 0px 1px; direction: ltr; box-shadow: rgb(53, 140, 203) -1px 0px 0px 0px, rgb(223, 223, 223) 0px 0px 0px 1px; position: relative; border-left: 10px solid rgb(53, 140, 203);\"><span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">{</span>\r\nid<span class=\"token operator\" style=\"color: rgb(166, 127, 89); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);\">:</span> integer<span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">,</span>\r\nname<span class=\"token operator\" style=\"color: rgb(166, 127, 89); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);\">:</span> <span class=\"token function\" style=\"color: rgb(221, 74, 104);\">varchar</span><span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">(</span><span class=\"token number\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 0, 85);\">255</span><span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">,</span>\r\ndescription<span class=\"token operator\" style=\"color: rgb(166, 127, 89); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);\">:</span> <span class=\"token function\" style=\"color: rgb(221, 74, 104);\">varchar</span><span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">(</span><span class=\"token number\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 0, 85);\">500</span><span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">,</span>\r\n<span class=\"token punctuation\" style=\"color: rgb(153, 153, 153);\">}</span>​</code></pre><br><br></li><li>Write the Postgres SQL for creating the tables for each model in all modules.</li><li>Write the Postgres SQL code for each of the following operations for each model:<ol><li>CREATE - Create a new resource</li><li>READ ALL- Retrieve all resources</li><li>READ ONE - Retrieve a single resource</li><li>UPDATE - Update a given resource</li><li>DELETE - Delete a given resource</li></ol></li><li>Write a set of unit tests that you think should be written or implemented for this application and why. For instance, you may say Item creation unit test should be implemented to test that a new item being created is not a duplicate that already exists in the database.</li><li>What design would you recommend for building this app and why?</li></ol><p><br></p><p>Upload your finished script and send as an attachment to 